{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"75af239c-0ff2-4679-a4bc-4956ab276f1b","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\n        \"run\",\n        \"--project\",\n        \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"\n      ]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- Your MCP server must read JSON-RPC from **stdin** and write responses to **stdout** (use the [C# MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/csharp-sdk) for this).\n- Make sure your server does **not** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead.\n\nFor a **published/built** server, you can point directly at the DLL:\n\n```json\n\"command\": \"dotnet\",\n\"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"02299425-507d-4d6b-b54b-37d58216a62b","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"CC2C:E2933:7E374CA:8C81548:69EAC14F"},"id":"812ca286-1435-4748-94ff-dae994e271dc","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:03:19.653Z","parentId":"8074beb9-d5af-4718-87ae-c6f2d5010a8c"}
